node.text:
⭐️ Holding and writing with a pencil is hard!  It takes skillful control and lots of strength and endurance of all the small muscles in the hand. 

⭐️And the best way to develop these muscles is through PLAY!  Many everyday preschool activities help to  build up the strength and dexterity of those hands and fingers! 

⭐️So keep the days filled with play.  So when kindergarten rolls around in September, those little hands will be ready!

node.text:
Crossing Midline helps children build strong connections between the right and left sides of their brains so they can easily accomplish tasks and activities like crawling reciprocally, getting dressed, playing sports, reading, writing, and scanning a room. 

In the first few months, babies are already starting to cross midline visually, then when reaching for toys and rolling. 

Here are a few ways for you to challenge your baby with some crossing midline activities. 

Keep in mind that by giving your baby lots of floor time for tummy time, rolling, crawling etc. your baby will likely find crossing midline opportunities on his or her own so you don’t need to “work” on this skill-just incorporate lots of play and movement into your baby’s every day.

node.text:
We are excited to be partnering with @tiny.talkers who are focusing this week on early intervention and red flags to look out for during the pivotal first 3 years when so much growth is happening. 

Check out their page for posts with red flags in other areas of development. 

During the first few years, there are so many milestones that are being reached and ranges for when we expect them to come in like:

Rolling: 4-6 months 
Sitting: 6-7 months 
Crawling: 7-9 months 
Pulling to stand: 8-10 months 
Picking up Cheerios with 2 fingers: 9-10 months 
Walking: 10-15 months 
Standing up on the stairs: 18 months- 2 years Jumping: 2 years 
Drawing vertical & horizontal lines: 2.5-3 years 

What we also need to take note of, are the nuances that may signal for extra attention. 

In the post ☝️, we show some red (actually green) flags that are important to take note of and seek guidance from your pediatrician or OT or PT if you notice any of them.

It helps us stay balanced by adjusting our movements in relation to the outside environment. And providing lots of opportunities to channel the vestibular sense is so important starting early on!!

node.text:
Squats are like hard core exercises 💪💪💪, right??!

Yes! For both us adults, and our tots! Squats WORK! They work for strengthening the legs, glutes, and core in our kids the same way they do for us. 

But we can’t  just ask our toddlers or preschoolers (or grade schoolers) to do 10 reps 🤷🏼‍♀️.

No, but we can ask them to play with toys. And the way we set up those toys will make all the difference. Take toys that have large coins, puzzle pieces, or a game like Topple as shown here and place all the pieces on the floor and the target for those pieces on a table or chair. And get ready to watch your tot work it!!! 🏋️

Great exercise for kids learning to jump, negotiate stairs, climb ladders,  pedal a tricycle, and lots more!

node.text:
A newborn’s head is actually really soft because the skull hasn’t fully formed yet.

We want to make sure to prevent baby from developing flat spots on the back or sides of the head. Those flattenings can lead to tightening of the neck muscles or possibly facial asymmetries. Try these easy tips to help your baby develop a beautiful round head. 👶

If you notice a mild flat spot, there is no need to panic! There is still plenty of time for the skull to even out. However, if the flatness is significant, speak to your pediatrician or OT/PT to determine if a helmet is appropriate.
